---
import DefaultLayout from '../../layouts/DefaultLayout.astro'
import FullWidth from '../../components/FullWidth.astro'
import ContentMedia from '../../components/ContentMedia.astro'
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/DemandShapingComparisonTable.astro'
---

<DefaultLayout title="Demand Shaping">
    <section>
        <div class="container">
            <h1 class="text-center text-6xl md:text-left">
                Demand Shaping 
            </h1>
        </div>
    </section>
    <section class="mt-8">
        <div class="container">
            <p class="text-2xl">
                How to control the insatiable desire for more and more data 
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>
    <FullWidth>
        <h4 class="text-4xl">The Data Demand Problem</h4>
        <p class="text-xl">
            In the modern enterprise, demand is unpredictable: 
        </p>
        <ul class="text-xl list-warning">
            <li>
                BI dashboards spike at 9am
            </li>
            <li>
                Ad hoc queries unpredictably collide with scheduled pipelines
            </li>
            <li>
                AI agents generate bursts of exploratory queries
            </li>
            <li>
                One poorly written query can degrade performance for everyone
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-xl">
            To prevent failures (and associated penalties from SLA breaches), data teams <strong>overprovision</strong> their clusters and warehouses. 
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl">
            In other words, they pay for compute they never use. This is a <strong>wasted corporate asset</strong>.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl">
            And yet, failures still happen.
        </p>
    </FullWidth>
    <section class="mt-8" title="Demand Shaping Definition">
        <div class="container p-8">
            <h3>
                What is Demand Shaping?
            </h3>
            <p class="text-2xl">
                Demand Shaping is a practice borrowed from public utilities and retailers.
            </p>
            <br/>
            <p class="text-2xl">
                It is used by all the big hyperscalers to manage demand (such as queries) to economically fit current and anticipated supply (e.g., compute availability and budget).
            </p>
            <br/>
            <p class="text-2xl">
                Demand Shaping reduces the unit economics down to the query. You no longer size warehouses or manage clusters. 
            </p>
            <br/>
        </div>
    </section>
    <FullWidth>
        <p class="text-3xl">
            Which means your data lake is more stable and more efficient, no matter what you ask of it.
        </p><br/>
        <p class="text-3xl">    
            <strong>Only Icebreaker brings hyperscaler-grade Demand Shaping to the enterprise.</strong>
        </p>
    </FullWidth>
    <ContentMedia imgSrc="" reverseImg>
        <h2>1. Intelligent Query Admission Control</h2>
        <p class="text-xl">
            Unlike traditional warehouses that struggle when too many queries hit at once, Icebreaker utilizes an intermediate queue. 
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl">
            This allows the platform to hold SQL queries in a "buffer" while the optimal execution environment is prepared, preventing the "thundering herd" effect that usually leads to performance degradation.
        </p>
    </ContentMedia>
    <ContentMedia imgSrc="" >
    <h2>2. Granular Right-Sizing & Bin Packing</h2>
    <p class="text-xl">
        Icebreaker analyzes the requirements of every individual query before execution.
    </p>
    <ul class="text-xl">
        <li>
            <strong>Right-Sizing:</strong> It allocates only the necessary compute resources—no more, no less.
        </li>        
        <li>
            <strong>Bin Packing:</strong> Multiple queries are intelligently "packed" onto the same compute instances to eliminate idle time and maximize every cent of your spend.
        </li>
    </ul>
</ContentMedia>
    <ContentMedia imgSrc="" reverseImg>
    <h2>3. Fleet-Level Cost Optimization</h2>
    <p class="text-xl">
        Administrators can define Compute Fleets to dictate the underlying infrastructure. This gives you the power to:
    </p>
    <ul class="text-xl">
        <li>
            Maximize the use of <strong>Spot Instances</strong>, even for mission-critical queries.
        </li>
        <li>
            Use Reserved Instances (RIs) and Savings Plans for predictable baselines.
        </li>
        <li>
            Drastically lower unit economics by letting the platform choose the cheapest available compute that meets the query's requirements.
        </li>
    </ul>
</ContentMedia>
    <ContentMedia imgSrc="" >
    <h2>4. Configurable Priority & Pre-warming</h2>
    <p class="text-xl">
        You shouldn't have to choose between cost and speed for your most critical data.
    </p>
    <ul class="text-xl">
        <li>
            <strong>Pre-Warming:</strong> Automatically spin up instances for known peak times (like that 9 AM BI dashboard spike).
        </li>        
        <li>
            <strong>Workload Prioritization:</strong> Define which workloads get "VIP treatment." You can even configure preemption strategies where high-priority queries can safely bump lower-priority, background tasks.
        </li>
    </ul>
</ContentMedia>
<FullWidth>

        <h2>Compare Icebreaker with Your Data Platform</h2>
        <ComparisonTable title="Comparison between Traditional Warehouses and Icebreaker Data" />

</FullWidth>
</DefaultLayout>